6. ATR — Average True Range                    |
═══════════════════════════════════════════════
 
ATR answers ONE question:
    "How many dollars does this stock move per day on average?"
 
It does NOT generate a BUY or SELL vote.
It is used ONLY to size the stop-loss and take-profit after a signal fires.
 
  stop_loss   = entry_price − (ATR × 1.5)   ← for a BUY
  take_profit = entry_price + (ATR × 3.0)   ← for a BUY
 
  stop_loss   = entry_price + (ATR × 1.5)   ← for a SELL
  take_profit = entry_price − (ATR × 3.0)   ← for a SELL
 
  2:1 reward-to-risk ratio baked in (TP = 2 × SL distance)
 
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 
FORMULA:
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 
  Same True Range as ADX, but no directional component.
  ATR just smooths TR values — it only cares about SIZE, not direction.
 
  TR  = max(High−Low, |High−PrevClose|, |Low−PrevClose|)
  ATR = ewm(TR, alpha=1/14)
 
