Q: Why are there so many filters?
A: Each filter prevents a specific type of loss.
   ADX       → stops you losing to a trending market
   BandWidth → stops you fighting a breakout
   Volume    → stops you entering on a conviction move
   Weekly    → stops you trading against the macro trend
   Together they protect you from bad conditions.
 
Q: Which indicator is the most important?
A: Bollinger Bands + Z-Score are the CORE (they generate the actual signal).
   All other indicators are GUARDS that block bad entries.
 
Q: Can I disable the filters?
A: Yes, each filter has a parameter:
     require_volume    = False  → skip volume filter
     use_weekly_filter = False  → skip weekly trend filter
   But you'll lose money in the conditions they protect against.
 
Q: What is the difference between HOLD and EXIT?
A: HOLD  = no position, do nothing.
   EXIT  = you ARE in a trade and it's time to close it.
           (action=HOLD but signal_type=BB_MEAN_REVERT, reasoning starts with [EXIT])
 
Q: Why does EXIT use action=HOLD instead of action=EXIT?
A: The BaseStrategy validator only accepts BUY, SELL, or HOLD.
   EXIT intent is encoded as HOLD + signal_type=BB_MEAN_REVERT so downstream
   consumers can detect it by checking signal_type == "BB_MEAN_REVERT".
 
Q: Why is the confidence cap 0.88 and not 1.0?
A: Mean reversion is a probabilistic strategy. Even the strongest Z-Score
   doesn't guarantee a reversal. The cap reflects that uncertainty.
 
Q: Why 1.5 for the Z-Score threshold?
A: 1.5 standard deviations is the sweet spot — extreme enough to have
   a real edge, but not so rare that you get very few trades.
 
Q: What happens if there is no Volume column in the data?
A: The volume filter defaults to True (allow), so the strategy degrades
   gracefully and still generates signals without volume data.